				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">$50-100</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Privacy panels</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">$25-45</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">$150-300</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Pool safety fence (per ft)</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">$3-6</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">$15-30</td>
			</tr>
		</tbody>
	</table>

	<p><strong>Note:</strong> Prices typically include delivery and pickup for rentals. Installation may be additional.</p>

	<h2>Installation Considerations</h2>

	<h3>Site Preparation</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Clear debris and level ground if possible</li>
		<li>Mark underground utilities before any digging</li>
		<li>Ensure access for delivery vehicles</li>
		<li>Plan gate locations for traffic flow</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Securing Temporary Fencing</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Concrete blocks:</strong> Standard stabilization for panels</li>
		<li><strong>Sandbags:</strong> Alternative weighting option</li>
		<li><strong>Drive pins:</strong> For semi-permanent installation</li>
		<li><strong>Wind bracing:</strong> Required in exposed areas</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Stockton Wind Considerations</h3>
	<p>Delta breeze winds require extra attention:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Use additional weights on exposed sites</li>
		<li>Consider windscreen attachment carefully (increases wind load)</li>
		<li>Inspect daily during windy periods</li>
		<li>May need guy wires for tall or long runs</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Permits and Regulations</h2>

	<h3>Construction Sites</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Temporary fencing often required by building permits</li>
		<li>Must meet OSHA requirements for job sites</li>
		<li>May require specific heights and configurations</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Special Events</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Event permits may specify fencing requirements</li>
		<li>Fire department access requirements</li>
		<li>ADA accessibility considerations</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Residential</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Pool fencing must meet California safety codes even temporarily</li>
		<li>HOA approval may be needed</li>
		<li>Duration limits may apply in some areas</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Safety and Liability</h2>

	<h3>Responsibilities</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Maintain fence in safe condition throughout use</li>
		<li>Repair or report damage promptly</li>
		<li>Ensure gates function properly</li>
		<li>Keep area around fence clear</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Insurance Considerations</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Verify your liability coverage includes temporary structures</li>
		<li>Rental companies may require proof of insurance</li>
		<li>Event insurance typically required for public gatherings</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Working with Rental Companies</h2>

	<h3>Questions to Ask</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>What's included in the rental price?</li>
		<li>Who handles installation and removal?</li>
		<li>What are the minimum rental periods?</li>
		<li>What's your policy on damage?</li>
		<li>Do you offer delivery and pickup?</li>
		<li>What options for extending the rental period?</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Typical Rental Terms</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Minimum rental: Usually 28-30 days</li>
		<li>Delivery charges: Often flat rate or per-mile</li>
		<li>Installation: May be included or extra</li>
		<li>Damage responsibility: Usually renter's obligation</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Alternatives to Traditional Temporary Fencing</h2>

	<h3>Portable Dog Fences</h3>
	<p>For temporary pet containment:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Expandable exercise pens</li>
		<li>Modular pet fence systems</li>
		<li>Quick setup, easy to move</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Garden Fencing</h3>
	<p>For protecting plants and gardens:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Decorative wire panels</li>
		<li>Plastic garden fencing</li>
		<li>Bamboo screens</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Temporary Privacy Screens</h3>
	<p>For visual blocking without full fence:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Portable privacy screens</li>
		<li>Outdoor curtain systems</li>
		<li>Bamboo roll screens</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Transitioning to Permanent Fencing</h2>
	<p>If temporary fencing is bridging the gap until permanent installation:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Coordinate rental return with permanent fence schedule</li>
		<li>Avoid gaps in coverage (especially for pool safety)</li>
		<li>Some temporary fence suppliers also install permanent fencing</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Conclusion</h2>
	<p>Temporary fencing provides flexible solutions for short-term needs without the commitment of permanent installation. Whether you're managing a construction site, hosting an event, or protecting your property during renovations, there's a temporary fencing option that fits your situation and budget.</p>

	<p>The key is matching the fencing type to your specific needs—security level, duration, budget, and any regulatory requirements. For many situations, rental makes more sense than purchase, but evaluate your specific circumstances to make the best decision.</p>

	<p>Need help determining the right temporary or permanent fencing solution? Contact us to discuss your needs.</p>

